\pard\plain \tx360\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Now we\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92ll look at the \u8220\'93Comments & Footnotes\u8221\'94 pane\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 don\u8217\'92t worry about clicking on the button in the inspector header bar just yet though (for your reference, the \u8220\'93Comments & Footnotes\u8221\'94 button is the one with the \u8220\'93n.\u8221\'94 inside a square speech bubble).}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Comments and footnotes in Scrivener work a little like comments in Word or OpenOffice, but they\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92re not exactly the same. Let\u8217\'92s take a look at them.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 For a start, click on the orange highlighted text in the sentence below:}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
