\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Note how the inspector automatically switches to the Comments & Footnotes pane, and the comment associated with the text gets selected.}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Next, click on the grey footnote}{\f2\fs26\b0\i1  in the inspector}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 , directly below the highlighted comment.}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\qc\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs32\b0\i0 This sentence has a footnote }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://4ABF7FDD-A111-40AA-A9C2-811C5A585BB7"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs32\b0\i0 attached.}}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 See how clicking on the note in the inspector automatically selects the text associated with it in the main editor?}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 If you click on a note in the inspector, the editor will automatically scroll to the position in the text where the note has been placed. This allows you to use the comments and footnotes to navigate the text, which means you can use them for personal placeholders, too. Try scrolling to the bottom of this document, and then clicking the orange comment to return to the spot where it is anchored.}
\par\pard\plain \tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sb260\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs36\b0\i0\ul\ulc0 Adding Comments And Footnotes}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s try adding some comments and footnotes. There are a couple of ways of doing this. First, select some of the text in the following sentence:}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\qc\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs32\b0\i0 Select some of the text in this sentence.}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Once you\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92ve selected a word or two in the above sentence, either click on the \u8220\'93+\u8221\'94 button in the top \u8220\'93Comments & Footnotes\u8221\'94 bar in the inspector or use the }{\f3\fs26\b1\i0 Format > Comment}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0  menu command. A new comment will be created in the inspector and it will be selected ready for editing\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 add some text. Once you\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92ve finished typing in the comment, tap the }{\f3\fs26\b1\i0 Esc}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0  key to return to the editor.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Alternatively, you can just click into or after a word to add a comment or footnote to it. This time, just click into the word \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93commented\u8221\'94 below so that the blinking insertion point (or caret) is somewhere inside it:}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\qc\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs32\b0\i0 This sentence will be commented.}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Again, create a comment using your preferred method. Note how the whole word \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93commented\u8221\'94 gets a comment associated with it.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s try it with a footnote too. Place the cursor anywhere in the last word of the following sentence:}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\qc\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs32\b0\i0 This sentence will have a footnote after it when exported or printed.}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\fi560\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 This time, click on the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93+fn\u8221\'94 button in the inspector (note that you can add icons for \u8220\'93Footnote\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93Comment\u8221\'94 to the Format Bar by using }{\f3\fs26\b1\i0 Tools > Customize Toolbar\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8230\'85}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 ).}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Note how the footnote gets attached to the word \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93printed\u8221\'94, including the full stop. It generally doesn\u8217\'92t matter where you attach comments, because they are usually for your own (or collaborators\u8217\'92) reference only, but with footnotes you should always ensure that the footnote link (the grey highlight) ends at exactly in the place you want the footnote number to appear when printed or exported. Since the footnote highlight ends right after the full stop, that means the footnote number will be inserted there, which is usually what you will want.}
